observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

strictly adhere to the state policy on DRRM by giving priority on the approval and implementation of planned PPAs to achieve the objectives/goals of the government of a disaster resilient environment;

explain/present accurate report/record with regards to the cited utilization of 30 per cent DRRM fund on typhoon related expenses without any declaration of state of calamity; 

ensure that the implementation of DRRM projects/distribution of relief goods is in accordance with updated DRRM Implementing Plan/Detailed Budget Proposal for transparency and systematic operation;


present the copy of the Agency’s DRRM Implementing Plan for verification;

facilitate immediately the submission of the cited unsubmitted DV and its supporting documents and liquidation report; and 

submit DRRM liquidation reports on a timely manner.

We recommended that Management:

follow the applicable provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as a basis for reconciling the accounting PPE accounts and RPCPPE, IIRUP, ledger cards, missing PPEs, and other related PPE management record/reports;

designate personnel for each of the accounting and property offices who shall maintain and update the PPE Ledger/Property Cards and regularly reconcile their records, as well as maintain updated ARE with the complete and specific description and safekeeping of all pertinent documents relative to the acquisition of properties;

direct the General Services Officer to attend trainings/workshops  about PPE Management;

assign an adequate number of personnel, in the GSO to properly facilitate, monitor and update ARE, Property Cards, and other reports pertaining to the management of the Municipality’s PPE; and

indicate in the RPCPPE, IIRUP, and other related PPE records/reports the actual condition of the PPE as validated during the inventory for proper monitoring and reporting of unserviceable properties subject to disposal.

We recommended that Management:

strictly adhere to the state policy on DRRM by giving priority to the full implementation of planned PPAs to achieve the objectives/goals of the government in a disaster-resilient environment;

submit Purchase Orders and their supporting documents within five days from their issuance to COA following COA Circular No. 2009-001, for contract review/evaluation;

direct the head of MDRRMO to prepare the Agency’s DRRM Implementing Plan;

ensure that the LDRRMFIP being implemented is consistent with the LDRRMFIP submitted as part of the Annual Budget and the final and approved plan by the Sanggunian Bayan; and

employ appropriate action on the management issues within the MDRRM Office.

We recommended that Management:

direct the GAD Focal Point Chairperson in close coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer to prepare the GAD plan and budget and ensure the allocation of at least 5% of the total annual appropriations for GAD-related activities;

direct the GFPS to design programs and activities that will respond to the identified gender issues and concerns both organization and client-focused and prepare a more realistic and attainable GPB to ensure that GAD projects will be carried out per the approved plan as well as implement a defined monitoring and evaluation system to properly assess the status and impact of GAD PPAs on gender mainstreaming;

direct the concerned implementer of GAD PPAs to facilitate full implementation of PPAs assigned to them; and

endorse the designated GFPS to GAD-related training for their necessary knowledge and skills in heading GAD plan formulation, budgeting, implementation, and reporting.

We recommended that Management: 

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that ORs issued in the infirmary reflect the itemized medical services billed to the patient and ensure that only authorized, properly designated, and bonded employees are allowed to handle the infirmary’s collections;

ensure that billing statements were pre-numbered for control and monitoring purposes and copies thereof are properly filed in the Infirmary and attached to corresponding ORs in the Report of Collections and Remittance/Deposits; 

direct the Municipal Treasurer to instruct collecting officer to include the doctor’s fees in the ORs issued and include its corresponding amount in her collections for subsequent payment to the doctor on duty of his/her monthly honorarium for proper recording of income in the books;

require the Sagñay Infirmary personnel to exert their best efforts in accounting for all the unpaid hospital bills and promissory notes, and submit a report to the Municipal Accountant for appropriate recording in the books to establish the outstanding unpaid hospital bills and ensure monitoring of settlements thereof;



direct the Chief of Hospital/Head of Sagñay Infirmary to establish a concrete internal guideline in the execution of promissory notes in accordance with R.A. 9439 and together with the Municipal Treasurer adopt an effective control in recording and settlement of promissory notes;

stop the withholding of birth certificates as collateral to promissory notes;

coordinate with PhilHealth to establish the total amount of unpaid claims and require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary records for PhilHealth receivables and regularly conduct monitoring and reconciliation with PhilHealth’s records;



increase to reasonable number of manpower in Sagñay Infirmary to be able to properly segregate duties and responsibilities and to provide adequate medical services effectively and efficiently to its constituents;

seek additional funding for the repair/rehabilitation of the Infirmary; and

conduct a comprehensive evaluation of the operations and financial system of the Sagñay infirmary and institutionalize a clearly defined procedures and guidelines on the granting of medical health care assistance to qualified constituents to prevent further losses in its operations.

We recommended that Management:

direct the concerned project proponent of BFAR-MMK 2019 project to submit the required documents such as approved MOAs, list of beneficiaries and their complete address for proper validation;

institute appropriate and immediate action to repair the defective fiber glass boats in accordance with applicable rules and regulations so that it could be fully utilized as intended and submit liquidation report;

ensure that project drawing/layout are prepared and submitted together with contract documents as prescribed under procurement law; 

strictly adhere to COA Circular No. 94-013 and approved MOA in the implementation of projects under fund transfer.

We recommended that Management:

formalize the designation and responsibilities of PCF custodians and reiterate therein the prescribed PCF policies including the 75% replenishment requirement;

direct the PCF Custodians to facilitate approval of their estimates of one-month petty expenses for which the PCF is intended, and attach the said approved estimates to the ALOBS or Obligation Request for certification by Municipal Budget Officer; 


ensure complete PCF liquidation and/or refund at year-end; and


actualize refund within CY 2022 the beginning balance of ₱11,298.30 that has been outstanding since CY 2011 and 2015.

We recommended that Management:

conduct regular monitoring of on-going construction to ensure that appraisal and assessment on the building are issued upon completion of construction; 

conduct regular inspection of real properties to validate actual or predominant use of property to provide assurance that collections are based on correct, accurate and credible assessments.

We recommended that Management:

conduct a complete inventory of all the supplies and materials inventory and submit a complete inventory report of all supplies inventoried to the audit team; 

direct the General Services Office to maintain complete supply ledger cards and stock cards and maintain a strong internal control on property management system for appropriate recording and ensure that all property is safeguarded and accounted for;

direct the concerned management personnel on the distribution of relief goods and other supplies and materials for distribution to submit the necessary reports/records, RSMI and supporting documents such as distribution lists to accounting unit for proper accounting and recording in the books; and  

direct the Municipal Accountant to record the appropriate accounts upon submission of the RSMI and the appropriate supporting documents.

